    "title": "IGAD pushes free movement protocol in Somalia consultations",
    "original_title": "IGAD Mobilises Stakeholders to Advance the Free Movement of Persons Protocol",
    "slug": "igad-pushes-free-movement-protocol-in-somalia-consultations",
    "summary": "IGAD convened Somali stakeholders including workers, journalists, and officials in Mogadishu to build support for ratifying and implementing the Free Movement of Persons Protocol, aiming to ease cross-border travel and boost regional integration.",
    "content": "The Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD) held a meeting in Mogadishu on Wednesday to rally support for its Protocol on Free Movement of Persons. Workers' organizations, media representatives, and government officials from Somalia participated in the discussions, part of a wider regional push to advance the agreement. The protocol is designed to enable safe, orderly, and regular travel across IGAD member states, with the goal of deepening economic and social ties within the region.\n\nThis initiative is part of IGAD's ongoing assistance to Somalia in moving the protocol forward. The plan requires national ratification and implementation, which has been slow in some countries due to concerns over security, border management, and labor market impacts. For Somalia, advancing the protocol could facilitate the movement of people, including refugees and diaspora members, who often face bureaucratic hurdles when traveling or resettling within the IGAD bloc.\n\nThe consultation in Mogadishu focused on building consensus among key constituencies. Workers' groups emphasized the need to protect labor rights and ensure that free movement does not lead to exploitation. Journalists highlighted the role of media in informing the public about the benefits and challenges of the protocol, while government officials discussed legal and administrative steps needed for ratification.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, who frequently travel between Somalia and other IGAD countries such as Kenya, Ethiopia, and Djibouti, this protocol could simplify visa processes, reduce travel costs, and enhance business opportunities. It may also foster greater cultural exchange and family reunification. However, implementation will require coordinated efforts to address security concerns, particularly given Somalia's ongoing fight against militant groups and the need to prevent illegal movement.\n\nIGAD's regional campaign comes amid broader efforts to boost integration in the Horn of Africa. While the protocol was first adopted in 2020, only a few member states have fully ratified it. The engagement in Somalia is part of a strategy to accelerate the process, with similar consultations planned in other countries. Advocates argue that freer movement of people is essential for trade, investment, and stability across the region.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/08/igad-mobilises-stakeholders-to-advance-the-free-movement-of-persons-protocol/?utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=igad-mobilises-stakeholders-to-advance-the-free-movement-of-persons-protocol",
